  <!-- ===== VERDICT ===== -->
  <div class="tab-content" id="tab-verdict">

    <div class="recommendation-box">
      <h3>⬡ Recommendation: Canaan — with targeted negotiation</h3>
      <p>
        For Truvet SG as a <strong>GMP-certified, HSA-regulated pharmaceutical manufacturing facility targeting an institutional trade sale or SGX IPO</strong>, the equipment selection decision is not purely a price-per-machine exercise. It is a regulatory infrastructure decision.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Canaan is the correct vendor for the core granulation and packaging line.</strong> The FDA 21 CFR Part 11 compliance — covering electronic signatures, audit trails, batch tracing — is not cosmetic: it is the minimum electronic system requirement that will be scrutinised by HSA during GMP inspection, and by any acquirer conducting technical due diligence. Urban does not document this capability in its quotations.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>However, Canaan's granulation line has a significant capacity design problem:</strong> the LHS75 High Shear Mixer produces 15–30 kg batches, while the downstream Film Coater (BGX75) handles 20–60 kg and the Roller Compactor handles up to 80 kg/h. You will require 2–3 HSM cycles per coater/compactor cycle, building in a structural bottleneck from day one. This must be raised and resolved with Canaan — either by upgrading to the LHS150 or equivalent, or by accepting this as a phase-1 throughput limitation.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Urban's capsule filling machine (NJP-800C at $26K) is the only category where Urban is clearly superior on both throughput and completeness</strong> — twice the speed, polisher and metal detector included, at 40% higher price. Consider sourcing this from Urban separately if Canaan's NJP-400C is inadequate for projected capsule volumes.
      </p>
    </div>

